<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Cheshire West and Chester Council - Response to Local Government Procurement, Commons Select Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written submission from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cheshire West and Chester Council</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (LPG 49)</span></p><h1 style="font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Introduction</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This response has been submitted jointly by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Chrisi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Lloyd-Roberts, Senior Procurement Manager, Cheshire West and Chester Council and Andy Moran, Director, Plan Procure Manage Limited.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Cheshire West and Chester Council was formed following a local government reorganisation in 2009. Since then the Council  has continued to transform and improve the way it works in particular in the area of procurement. The Council this year won the ‘GO’ procurement award for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Best Customer Engagement Initiative of the Year and has commenced a major review of the delivery of all its services through a ‘Make or Buy’ programme. </span></h2><h1 style="font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Summary</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This submission provides evidence from Cheshire West and Chester Council (CWAC) as to what actions it has taken to transform its procurement activity since its establishment in 2009 including;</span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Response to Public Services (Social Value) Act and the CWAC Procurement and Commissioning Strategy 2013 to 2016</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">How procurement of a £100m Housing Management contract was used to contribute to local economic development and the engagement and involvement of residents</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Strategic Commissioning Body model and the CWAC ‘Make or Buy’ programme to review future delivery models for services including engagement with residents</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Contracting strategy for major projects and relationship management</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Collaborative procurements by CWAC and shared services initiatives</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Approach to establishing a Commercial Management function and the skills required</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Management information processes for expenditure analysis, market intelligence and engagement with suppliers</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Approach to risk management, evaluation and mitigation</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Business processes implemented to reduce fraud and increase transparency</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><h1 style="font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Response</span></h1><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">1. To what extent is local government procurement organised to deliver value for money and social, economic and environmental objectives, including stimulating the local economy? </span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Public Services (Social Value) Act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ha</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s provided a catalyst for local authorities to re-evaluate how they can lever additional benefits from their procurement activity. Cheshire West and Chester (CWAC) have incorporated this aim into its 2013 – 2016 Procurement and Commissioning Strategy with the following objectives;</span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To include environmental considerations in funding, contract policy and purchasing decisions with reference to the Carbon Reduction Plan; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To ensure that the principles of sustainability, economic development and equality are promoted and addressed, as appropriate, in all procurement and contracting activities; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To ensure that Council procedures do not exclude any company - whether small to medium size enterprise (SMEs), voluntary or community sector (VCS), or otherwise - from the opportunity to bid for Council business; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Reviewing the Council’s present approach to resource use. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CWAC Commissioning and Procurement Strategy 2013 – 2016</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:17.85pt"><a href="http://cmttpublic.cheshirewestandchester.gov.uk/mgConvert2PDF.aspx?ID=31751"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://cmttpublic.cheshirewestandchester.gov.uk/mgConvert2PDF.aspx?ID=31751</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">An example of where this approach has been utilised is the Ellesmere Port and Neston</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Housing Management contract that CWAC procured in 2012. The award criteria and corresponding contract specification included a requirement for bidder’s proposals relating to; tackling </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">worklessness</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and improving access to training/employment; ensuring local suppliers are not disadvantaged when procuring goods and services; and increasing apprenticeships. This requirement was specifically targeted at the most disadvantaged groups including lone parents, ex-offenders, substance users, young adults and long-term unemployed residents.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In July 2013 CWAC commenced a programme to review the delivery of all its services to baseline current performance, appraise and determine the best future delivery model known as the ‘Make or Buy’ programme. The reviews will consider future options for services against a number of criteria including what contribution could be made to local economic development primarily through creating work and training opportunities for local people and how the local supplier base will be supported. </span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">To what extent are local authorities achieving the involvement of local residents in delivering value for money? </span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The CWAC Make or Buy programme commenced with a public consultation that is currently ongoing, asking residents their views on different delivery models i.e. in-house, shared services with public sector partners, council owned companies, private sector, voluntary or charitable organisations, co-operatives and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mutuals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The consultation also asks residents to rank various priorities to be taken into account </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">during the Make or Buy service reviews; including cost, deliverability, quality, social value and risk.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Link to Make or Buy Consultation </span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:28.8pt"><a href="http://www.cheshirewestandchester.gov.uk/pdf/20130726_makeorbuy.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.cheshirewestandchester.gov.uk/pdf/20130726_makeorbuy.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CWAC won the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2013/14 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government Opportunities ‘GO’ Award for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Best Customer Engagement Initiative of the Year for the involvement of tenants in the Ellesmere Port and Neston Housing Management contract.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A tenants group was formed to play a fundamental part in the procurement process. The initial action was for the procurement and legal team to provide an overview to tenants of the procurement process. It included an explanation of how, in practice, the procurement regulations operate and how competitive dialogue would be undertaken, and their role in the process. In addition, the tenants were supported by an independent advisor, who was the organiser and facilitator for the group. The tenants took the lead in drafting elements of the service specification, determining the evaluation criteria (including weighting), and the evaluation of bidder submissions at each stage of the process.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whilst very time consuming for the tenants and for officers this proved a very useful process. It involved ‘looking back’ at how the service had evolved and also ‘looking forward’ to show the expectations for bidders. There were reality checks made about the expectations particularly around the cost of providing an enhanced service which could inflate the contract price and be unaffordable.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The result of the activity was that the tenants had ownership of the process and, with support of the independent advisor, they led the discussions with bidders in dialogue meetings. Tenants were able to clearly articulate their aims for the service delivery, and priorities for their community. Bidders were clear that the tenants evaluation would have a significant impact on the selection of the successful contractor.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Prior to procurement CWAC systematically consider whether resident/service user consultation is appropriate (see attached consultation guide for officers).  This is additional to the existing stakeholder engagement obligations in the Compact with the Third Sector Assembly representing the Voluntary, Community and Faith sectors. </span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="102" height="67" alt="" /></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">To what extent are local authorities able to develop long-term relationships with contractors?</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A present there is a tension between developing long-term relationships with contractors and the need to fundamentally redesign services to deliver the best outcomes for residents from reduced resources. For contractors to deliver culture change and a return on any significant level of investment this typically requires </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">minimum 5 year contract duration. Due to the current pace of change for local authorities, particularly in relation to increasing responsibilities and reducing funding, this can result in a barrier to committing to long term contracts as there is a concern that this will create areas of spend which are then in effect ‘ring-fenced’ when further savings are required. </span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Following on from the work that CWAC have done on their Housing and Waste Management contracts, a contracting approach has been developed that is based on common outcomes and understandings, between the council and contractors that includes;</span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an initial period of guaranteed cost savings</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">open book accounting</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">changes based on a ‘no better, no worse’ financial basis</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">shared risk and reward</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">continuous improvement</span></li></ul><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In developing this approach CWAC are engaging with major contractors of public services to understand their drivers and constraints, whilst ensuring that flexibility is built into future contracts.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">2. Do authorities take sufficient advantage of collaborative and joint procurement opportunities, including those available from central government? In addition, the Committee would welcome information on PFI contracts and their operation with local government.</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CWAC has proactively engaged in collaborative procurement through a number of initiatives;</span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Highways Maintenance – joint procurement with Shropshire County Council and plans to establish a joint client management and professional services team in 2014</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Construction – using the North West Construction Hub for delivery of its major capital projects including leisure centres and a new theatre</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Utilities – purchasing electricity via the West Mercia Energy consortium</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Corporate – buying from a range of Government Procurement Service frameworks</span></li></ul><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In July 2013 CWAC and Wirral councils have committed to exploring establishing a joint back office resources service including procurement. The combined spend of the two councils is approximately £400m per year which gives a significantly increased power in the market particularly for corporate goods and services. </span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As part of the Make or Buy programme CWAC have initiated discussions with other local authorities on future shared delivery models. This is initially in the areas of Schools Support, Highways and Customer Services. These discussions are at very early stages to investigate potential opportunities for shared management and service delivery to achieve efficiencies.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CWAC has a single PFI contract for six primary schools that is relatively low value therefore we have no specific comments to contribute.</span></h2><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">3. How can local authorities access the skills, expertise and capabilities to implement effective procurement strategies, including value for money and social and economic objectives? </span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CWAC are implementing a fundamental change to become a Strategic Commissioner, and a move from focusing on service delivery to commissioning for outcomes.  This requires reassessment of the organisational structure of the Council that differentiates between strategic decision making and the delivery of services. </span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.18</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">trategic element of the organisation is the one that sets the direction and determines how the available resources, (including financial), are to be arranged and deployed. This is the core decision making function. The remaining elements are; Managerial, (i.e. the delivery of the strategic direction by deploying the Operational resources in an effective and efficient manner), and Operational, (i.e. the resources which are utilised for service delivery). </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.20</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The rationale for the review of the organisational structure will be to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reduce the resources required for both the managerial activity, (through a consistent approach to contract management and the establishment of commercial management</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">), and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reduce </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the cost of operational activity through the process of service redesign, and the identification and appraisal of different options for delivery, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(essentially the process of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ‘Make or Buy’ programme).  </span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.21</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The change to becoming a Strategic Commissioning body means that the capabilities required within procurement teams have shifted from traditional buying skills to more rounded commercial skill set, including negotiation skills and market awareness along with contract and risk management. </span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.22</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The existing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">skill ba</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">se of procurement officers has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been predominately focused on a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dministering the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> tendering activity, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and as a result </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local authorities have employed commercial consultants where there has been a requirement for large scale pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">curement activity in particular</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> those involving competitive dialogue. This has resulted in a lack of skills development within procurement teams and limited transfer of knowledge.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.23</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Establishing these skills within the council is key to ensuring the outcomes proposed by suppliers are delivered and relationships are developed to maximise the benefits of long term partnerships. CWAC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have commenced the establishment of a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> commercial management team to include:</span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.42pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Contract management and administration</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.42pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Project management</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.42pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Risk management</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.42pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Strategic thinking and decision making</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.42pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Financial modelling</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.42pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Contract law</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.42pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Negotiation and competitive dialogue</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">More specifically, does local government have sufficient understanding of its procurement expenditure and the markets for goods and services to deliver quality procurement strategies—locally and regionally. If not, how can deficiencies be addressed?</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.24</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CWAC have detailed and validated reporting on expenditure that is categorised using the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Proclass</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">/National Supplier Vocabulary codes. This information is used to inform and prioritise the procurement strategy and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">workplans</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.25</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As regards Market knowledge this is split within commissioning, procurement and service teams. The Make or Buy programme is bringing together these various sources and collating them as part of the service review process. In addition these reviews also include research and case studies of local authority service provision across the UK to help identify best practice and opportunities for possible collaboration.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.26</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Pre-procurement market engagement is undertaken to inform the specification and design of the service/goods and also to validate that the market can deliver the outcomes being sought. Contractors can also be a useful source of market intelligence of other procurement processes being planned or in progress.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.27</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o facilitate engage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ment with local suppliers CWAC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is implementing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> digital portal to communicate with and support predominately</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> small business economy.  This tool will be used for low value procurement activity, (under £50K), to source </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local supply chain and to facilita</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">te subcontracting opportunities from larger tier 1 suppliers of the major contracts and projects, for example in construction. As part of the establishment of the commercial management team, and to improve the identification and mitigation of risk, a ‘tiered’ supplier categorisation system is being developed and will be start to be implemented on the major contracts during 2013/14.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">4. To what extent is risk in local government procurement and contracting understood and managed and contracting strategies adopted, which are tailored to product and supplier market places? </span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.28</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CWAC have changed the approach to risk management in contracts away from the previous approach of fixed insurance levels, indemnities etc to one where the benefits and risks are assessed and then the risk is allocated based on which party is best able to manage and mitigate that risk. This assessment also takes into account the commercial position of the council and is utilised to support negotiations with contractors. </span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.29</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Pre-procurement engagement is key to assessing what the market approach is to various risks. Reaching agreement on risks that are specific to the public sector, e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">those related to pensions, has the potential to significantly prolong the procurement process. Discussion of these issues and reaching a settled position within the council which should reasonably be accepted by contractors, prior to commencing procurement is key to ensuring the tendering process is as efficient as possible.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.30</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For contracts where payment by results is included bidding contractors are asked what percentage of the contract price they are willing to risk against meeting the performance standards. This is then included as a criteria in the price evaluation. This challenges contractors to demonstrate the confidence they have in delivery of their proposals.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.31</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At CWAC there is a structured approach to risk identification that is embedded in the commissioning, procurement and project management process. Risk analysis and reviews are undertaken at regular points during projects from the initial project mandate through to contract signing and are continued </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">through out</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the duration of the contract.</span></h2><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">More specifically, do local authorities maintain and operate effective client management functions and have they entered contractual arrangements which allow the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">flexibility to meet changing circumstances such as budget reductions or changes in the way a service has to be delivered?</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.32</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CWAC’s approach to commercial managem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ent is detailed in paragraphs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 3.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">18  to 3.24</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.33</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CWAC’s approach to flexibility in contracts is detailed in paragraphs 3.11 to 3.13.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">5. How is regularity and propriety of procurement secured and are the arrangements for detecting and addressing impropriety and fraud effective? </span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.34</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CWAC have implemented the following to reduce the risk of impropriety and fraud;</span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A centralised process and greater transparency in spending have helped to reduce the risk of fraud.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A ‘Compliance Team’ has been established to ensure that prior to purchase orders being issued to suppliers that a procurement process, that meets the Contract Procedure Rules and where applicable the relevant legislation, has been undertaken. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Procurement controls and compliance have improved with the introduction of the ORACLE </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">finance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">system, e.g. three way matching of invoices; enforced approval rout</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; audit trial that lists all updates to a suppliers record, i.e. who made the change and when; segregation of duties in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the order authorisation process;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">restrictions on spend in accordance with delegated financial authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All requests for a change in supplier must be in writing (on headed note paper signed by a Company director) with further verification checks made to confirm the relevant information.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">requests for manual cheque</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> requests,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a purchase and sup</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">plier invoice must be presented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> prior to any payment being made to suppliers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A workflow process </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which intercepts all order requisitions over £10,000 to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eithe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r a contract or the relevant approval is in place </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">waiving the contract procedure rules. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Increasing the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">use </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of electronic catalogues, thereby increasing the use of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contracted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">suppliers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and reducing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">buying from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">non-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contracted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> suppliers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A declaration of interest register has been instituted on all major projects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for employees and consultants.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The standard tender documentation includes an Anti-Collusion Certificate which has to be signed by bidders and is included in the final contract to be legally binding, and also makes reference to the Bribery Act 2010</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Spend and recovery audits. The payments system is audited for controls assurance e.g. duplicate payments to detect false invoicing and the recovery of over-payments. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">6. Is local authority procurement fully transparent, audited effectively and does it provide appropriate mechanisms for redress? Specifically, are the arrangements for securing the accountability of procured services and goods to local authorities and local residents adequate and effective? More specifically, to what extent are local authorities able to provide assurance to central government that value for money (in the broadest sense of the term) is delivered?</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.9pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.35</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The CWAC constitution sets out the governance and decision making process for the award of contracts. All contracts that require ‘Key Decisions’ by the council’s Executive are published in the council’s Forward Plan of decisions in the next 4 months. The decisions on these contracts are taken at the public meetings of the Executive and reports are published on the council’s website 7 days prior to the meeting. </span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.36</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">During 2012/13 CWACs Public Accounts Scrutiny Panel established a Procurement Task Group to investigate the effectiveness of the council’s consultation process relating to procurement. The task group is due report later this year. Further information relating to consultation and engagement of residents in the procurement process has been included earlier in this submission.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.37</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As part of its Open Data website CWAC publish a register of contracts which lists all contracts that have a value over £50,000 with the aim to include all contracts. CWAC also publish monthly all payments to suppliers over £500.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.38</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ayment is linked to performance wherever possible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o ensure value for money and accountability. The best example of this is the Waste Collection and Recycling contract where the commercial model is linked to the cost of waste disposal and incentivises the contractor to maximise the collection of recycling and to maximise the value of the materials collected. This has the effect of that each tonne of waste is valuable rather than a cost and has resulted in a 40% guaranteed saving.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.39</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All the contracts include rights of audit, intervention and termination that the council can exercise in the event of repeated poor performance and failure.</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>